/a/QnLb2qhREemTmMMyWK7bfA","annotation":"Subject: conceptualisation of system\nPredicate: can use\nObject: system conceptualisation tools\n\nSubject: system conceptualisation tools\nObject: aids to thinking showing how model drivers are linked to internal (state) variables and outputs (observed responses)\nObject: influence diagrams\nObject: linguistic model\nObject: block diagram\nObject: bond graph\n\nSubject: system conceptualisation tools\nPredicate: reference\nObject: Gawthrop and Smith, 1996\nObject: Wellstead, 1979","subject":"system conceptualisation","predicate":"can use","object":"system conceptualisation tools"},{"text":"Conceptualisation refers to basic premises about the working of the system being modelled","position":19,"link":"https://hypothes.is/a/PDEr3KhREemaAEsUkg6svA","annotation":"Subject: conceptualisation of the system\nPredicate: definition\nObject: definition of basic premises about the working of the system being modelled","subject":"system conceptualisation","predicate":"definition","object":"definition of basic premises about the working of the system being modelled"},{"text":"Boundary conditions can then be modelled as constraints or as input scenarios, whose values can be perturbed in line with stipulated assumptions.","position":20,"link":"https://hypothes.is/a/KDvB5qhREemVscMhRTMd9g","annotation":"Subject: define boundaries\nPredicate: has subtask\nObject: define boundary conditions\n\nSubject: define boundary conditions\nPredicate: can use\nObject: modelled as constraints or as input scenarios, whose values can be perturbed in line with stipulated assumptions","subject":"define boundary conditions","predicate":"can use","object":"modelled as constraints or as input scenarios, whose values can be perturbed in line with stipulated assumptions"},{"text":"Boundary conditions can then be modelled as constraints or as input scenarios, whose values can be perturbed in line with stipulated assumptions.","position":20,"link":"https://hypothes.is/a/KDvB5qhREemVscMhRTMd9g","annotation":"Subject: define boundaries\nPredicate: has subtask\nObject: define boundary conditions\n\nSubject: define boundary conditions\nPredicate: can use\nObject: modelled as constraints or as input scenarios, whose values can be perturbed in line with stipulated assumptions","subject":"define boundaries","predicate":"has subtask","object":"define boundary conditions"},{"text":"The system being modelled should be defined clearly, including its boundaries (e.g. physical, socioeconomic and institutional).","position":21,"link":"https://hypothes.is/a/IQXT-KhREemTlmPu3hT8uA","annotation":"Subject: conceptualisation\nPredicate: has subtask\nObject: clearly define system being modelled\nObject: define boundaries\n\nSubject: define boundaries\nPredict: description\nObject: clearly define boundaries (e.g. physical, socioeconomic and institutional)\n","subject":"define boundaries","predicate":"has subtask","object":"clearly define boundaries (e.g. physical, socioeconomic and institutional)"},{"text":"The system being modelled should be defined clearly, including its boundaries (e.g. physical, socioeconomic and institutional).","position":21,"link":"https://hypothes.is/a/IQXT-KhREemTlmPu3hT8uA","annotation":"Subject: conceptualisation\nPredicate: has subtask\nObject: clearly define system being modelled\nObject: define boundaries\n\nSubject: define boundaries\nPredict: description\nObject: clearly define boundaries (e.g. physical, socioeconomic and institutional)\n","subject":"conceptualisation","predicate":"has subtask","object":"define boundaries"},{"text":"The system being modelled should be defined clearly, including its boundaries (e.g. physical, socioeconomic and institutional).","position":21,"link":"https://hypothes.is/a/IQXT-KhREemTlmPu3hT8uA","annotation":"Subject: conceptualisation\nPredicate: has subtask\nObject: clearly define system being modelled\nObject: define boundaries\n\nSubject: define boundaries\nPredict: description\nObject: clearly define boundaries (e.g. physical, socioeconomic and institutional)\n","subject":"conceptualisation","predicate":"has subtask","object":"clearly define system being modelled"},{"text":"What to include and what not to incorporate in a modelling activity should be addressed explicitly at the outset and iteratively revisited as far as resources allow.","position":22,"link":"https://hypothes.is/a/FnAU2qhREemJS-_UMy_KDw","annotation":"Subject: conceptualisation\nPredicate: has subtask\nObject: define scope\n\nSubject: define scope\nPredicate: synonym\nObject: What to include and what not to incorporate in a modelling activity \n\nPredicate: should be\nObject: addressed explicitly at the outset and iteratively revisited as far as resources allow","subject":"define scope","predicate":"should be","object":"addressed explicitly at the outset and iteratively revisited as far as resources allow"},{"text":"What to include and what not to incorporate in a modelling activity should be addressed explicitly at the outset and iteratively revisited as far as resources allow.","position":22,"link":"https://hypothes.is/a/FnAU2qhREemJS-_UMy_KDw","annotation":"Subject: conceptualisation\nPredicate: has subtask\nObject: define scope\n\nSubject: define scope\nPredicate: synonym\nObject: What to include and what not to incorporate in a modelling activity \n\nPredicate: should be\nObject: addressed explicitly at the outset and iteratively revisited as far as resources allow","subject":"define scope","predicate":"synonym","object":"What to include and what not to incorporate in a modelling activity"},{"text":"What to include and what not to incorporate in a modelling activity should be addressed explicitly at the outset and iteratively revisited as far as resources allow.","position":22,"link":"https://hypothes.is/a/FnAU2qhREemJS-_UMy_KDw","annotation":"Subject: conceptualisation\nPredicate: has subtask\nObject: define scope\n\nSubject: define scope\nPredicate: synonym\nObject: What to include and what not to incorporate in a modelling activity \n\nPredicate: should be\nObject: addressed explicitly at the outset and iteratively revisited as far as resources allow","subject":"conceptualisation","predicate":"has subtask","object":"define scope"},{"text":"Consideration and justification of options in defining the system warrant attention by modellers and their clients. ","position":23,"link":"https://hypothes.is/a/Ec7iWKhREem4xNM-KRF61Q","annotation":"Subject: conceptualisation\nPredicate: definition\nObject: consideration and justification of options in defining the system\n\nPredicate: requires\nObject: attention by both modellers and clients\n","subject":"conceptualisation","predicate":"requires","object":"attention by both modellers and clients"},{"text":"Consideration and justification of options in defining the system warrant attention by modellers and their clients. ","position":23,"link":"https://hypothes.is/a/Ec7iWKhREem4xNM-KRF61Q","annotation":"Subject: conceptualisation\nPredicate: definition\nObject: consideration and justification of options in defining the system\n\nPredicate: requires\nObject: attention by both modellers and clients\n","subject":"conceptualisation","predicate":"definition","object":"consideration and justification of options in defining the system"},{"text":"For some environmental systems one has the luxury of optimal experimental design where inputs (such as to a bioreactor) can be manipulated to enhance the identifiability of a model (e.g. Versyck et al., 1998, Walter and Pronzato, 1997). For most systems, however, we must at any given time accept the data that are available. On the other hand, modellers can play a more proactive role in designing future data collection exercises. Monitoring efforts in the global change community are amongst the most striking.","position":24,"link":"https://hypothes.is/a/iOfmpKhSEemm_EMP71xWyA","annotation":"Subject: data collection","subject":"data collection","predicate":"topic of","object":"For some environmental systems one has the luxury of optimal experimental design where inputs (such as to a bioreactor) can be manipulated to enhance the identifiability of a model (e.g. Versyck et al., 1998, Walter and Pronzato, 1997). For most systems, however, we must at any given time accept the data that are available. On the other hand, modellers can play a more proactive role in designing future data collection exercises. Monitoring efforts in the global change community are amongst the most striking."}]
